def open_grams_as_counter(filename):
    '''
    Assumes file format from the sort -c command line command
    Uses Counter so sets can be added easily.
    Also opens zip files
    '''
    if (os.path.splitext(filename)[1] == '.gz'):
        infile = gzip.open(filename, 'rt')
    else:
        infile = open(filename, 'r')

    with infile:
        lines = [l.strip().split(' ') for l in infile.read().splitlines()]  # split all words on line
        lines = {' '.join(l[1:]): int(l[0]) for l in lines}  # re-join n+1 words in each line
        return Counter(lines)

def open_grams_as_dataframe(directory):
    '''
    Loads all text files from the input directory into a dataframe, 
    parsing out the date value from the filename itself.
    Assumes text file format is from the sort -c command line command.
    Returns: dataframe['date', 'word', 'count']
    '''
    df = pd.DataFrame(columns=['date', 'word', 'frequency'])
    
    for filename in glob.glob(os.path.join(directory, '*.txt')):
        data = pd.read_table(filename, delimiter='\s+', names=['frequency', 'word'])
        data['date'] = filename[-14:-4]
        data['date'] = pd.to_datetime(data['date'])
        data = data[['date', 'word', 'frequency']]  # reorder columns
        df = df.append(data)
    
    # set index and return
    df = df.set_index('date').sort_index()
    return df

def open_ngrams_as_dataframe(directory, tail: int=2):
    '''
    Loads all text files from the input directory into a dataframe,
    parsing out the date value from the filename itself.
    Also opens gzip files inside the directory.
    Tail is the lowest frequency. i.e. inlcude row if frequency > tail.
    Assumes text file format is from the sort -c command line command (i.e. read_fwf - fixed width file)
    Returns: dataframe['date', 'word', 'frequency']
    '''
    colNames = ['date', 'word', 'frequency']
    df = pd.DataFrame(columns=colNames)
    
    for filename in glob.glob(os.path.join(directory, '*')):
        if (os.path.splitext(filename)[1] == '.gz'):
            infile = gzip.open(filename, 'rt')
            date = pd.to_datetime(os.path.splitext(filename)[0][-14:-4]) # *.txt.gz
        else:
            infile = open(filename, 'r')
            date = pd.to_datetime(os.path.splitext(filename)[0][-10:]) # *.txt

        with infile:
            lines = [l.strip().split(' ') for l in infile.read().splitlines()]  # split all words on line
            lines = [[date, str(' '.join(l[1:])), int(l[0])] for l in lines] # re-join n+1 words in each line
            
            data = pd.DataFrame(lines, columns=colNames)
            data = data[data['frequency'] > tail]  # filter low frequency words
            df = df.append(data)
    
    # set index and return
    df['word'] = df['word'].apply(str)
    df = df.set_index('date').sort_index()
    return df
In [5]:
def get_top_shifts(s: sh.Shift, num: int = 0) -> list:
    '''
    Function to get the top-n words from a Shift graph.
    '''
    scores = s.get_shift_scores()
    if num == 0:
        return sorted(scores.items(), key=lambda k: abs(k[1]), reverse=True)
    if num > 0:
        return sorted(scores.items(), key=lambda k: abs(k[1]), reverse=True)[:num]
    else:
        return sorted(scores.items(), key=lambda k: abs(k[1]), reverse=True)[num:]

                          fields=['word'], nearest=True)

    x='date:T',
    y='frequency:Q',
    color='word:N',
#     strokeDash='word',
)

points = base.mark_circle(stroke="white", strokeWidth=5).encode(
    opacity=alt.value(0)
).add_selection(
    highlight
).properties(
    width=800
).interactive()

lines = base.mark_line().encode(
    size=alt.condition(~highlight, alt.value(1), alt.value(3)),
)
